1.  TYPE OF DATA

1.1  Parameter/Measurement.  Total solar irradiance at one Astronomical
Unit (1 A.U.), integrated over .2 to 50 micrometer wavelengths.  Standard
error is also calculated for each solar flux value.

1.2  Unit of Measurement.  Watts per meter squared (Watts/m**2).

1.3  Data Source.  Solar Maximum Mission's Active Cavity Radiometer
Irradiance Monitor (ACRIM I).

1.4  Data Set Identification.  The SMM/ACRIM data set contains averaged
daily solar irradiance values identified by the number of days into the
mission and the calendar date.


2.  SPATIAL CHARACTERISTICS

2.1  Spatial Coverage.  Full solar disk (Photosphere).

2.2  Spatial Resolution.  No resolution within the disk.


3.  TEMPORAL CHARACTERISTICS

3.1  Temporal Coverage.  February 19, 1980, to July 14, 1989.

3.2  Temporal Resolution.  Solar irradiances were measured every two
minutes (except between 1981 and 1983 when measurements were made once
about every 14 minutes).  Irradiances have been integrated over the orbital
period (96 minutes) and are available as daily mean values for this data
set.


4.  INSTRUMENT DESCRIPTION

4.1  Mission Objectives.  The objective of the Solar Maximum Mission was to
obtain measurements for the peak of solar cycle 21.  Solar cycles are
eleven-year cycles during which the number of sunspots increase to a
maximum.  The maximum for cycle 21 occurred in 1980.  Several experiments
are focused on the study of the impulsive phase of large flares.
Specifically, the ACRIM sensor was designed to begin a program of long-term
total solar irradiance monitoring.  For both long- and short- term solar
variations of significance to climate and solar physics, maximum precision
and accuracy were primary goals.

4.2  Key Satellite Flight Parameters.   For the Solar Maximum Mission:
     o  Launch Date         February 14, 1980
     o  Planned Duration    2  years
     o  Actual Duration     November 17, 1989
     o  Orbit Altitude      574 km.
     o  Nodal Period        96 minutes
     o  Instruments on
        board:              l.  Gamma Ray Spectrometer
                            2.  Hard X-ray Burst Spectrometer
                            3.  Hard X-ray Imaging Spectrometer
                            4.  X-ray Polychromator (failed)
                            5.  Ultraviolet Spectrometer & Polarimeter
                            6.  Coronagraph/Polarimeter
                            7.  Active Cavity Radiometer

4.3  Principles of Operation.  The ACRIM I is a pyrheliometer with a
conical-cavity detector, a shutter that can block solar radiation, and a
reference cavity that permanently views a surface at the temperature of a
heat sink.  A servo system maintains the observing cavity at a temperature
slightly above that of the reference cavity.  Measurements consist of
voltage determinations for the heater circuit in this servo loop.  A
difference between shutter-open and shutter-closed readings, normally
obtained in a two-minute cycle, then provides a measurement of solar
irradiance.

4.4  Instrument Measurement Geometry.  The self-calibrating pyrheliometer
views the sun through a five degree full angle field-of-view.  This angle
does not provide resolution within the solar disk.


5.  DATA PROCESSING SEQUENCE

5.1  Processing Steps and Data Sets.  The data are corrected for solar
distance (normalized to 1 A.U.), orbital displacement of the satellite, and
the shift in irradiance due to satellite motion. Temperature corrections
are also applied, and the data are integrated over a 96-minute orbital
period.  Daily mean values are calculated from orbital means.

Woodward and Hudson (1983) searched for the effects of a ("5 minute") solar
global oscillation phenomena in the original unintegrated total irradiance
data.  They found detectable irradiance variations with amplitudes for low
degree modes of up to a few parts per million in solar irradiance.

5.2  Derivation Techniques/Algorithms.  Daily mean values for this data set
are calculated from a variable number of daily input values, dependent on
the operating mode of the ACRIM.

A model to correct for background effects, which are dependent on the phase
of the satellite orbit, are applied to the data.  The model is composed of
two terms.  First, orbital motion causes a variable solar distance that
causes signal variations via the inverse-square law. Second, the motion of
the satellite produces a relativistic modulation of the detected signal.
The two effects together are described by:

                            2V
                              x      2X
               S = S ( 1 +  ----  + ---- )
                             C        R

where V (sub x) represents the satellite velocity component towards the sun
and the X represents the corresponding displacement from the Earth's
center.  The sum of these effects produces a sinusoidal modulation of the
apparent solar irradiance, with the peak shifted about 0.1 phase units past
the subsolar point of the orbit.

5.3  Special Corrections/Adjustments.  The ACRIM experiment operated in the
electrically self-calibrated mode to realize maximum accuracy and
precision.  During normal SMM operations, its shutters alternated every 64
seconds between collecting solar data and reference data.  In this mode,
more than 800 independent samples of total solar irradiance were acquired
during the 55-sunlit minutes of each 96-minute SMM orbit.

The solar pointing system of the Solar Maximum Mission failed in December
1980, and the satellite was placed into a spin stabilized mode with its
spin axis nominally directed at the sun.  Since SMM was not designed for
spin stabilization, this axis wobbled slowly about the solar direction with
a maximum pointing error of about 10 degrees.

The ACRIM I experiment was placed into a new operating mode to take
advantage of the limited solar pointing provided by the spin stabilized
spacecraft.  Instead of the normal opening and closing of ACRIM I's
shutters every minute, the shutters were opened only at orbit sunrise and
were closed at sunset.  This procedure produced an average of 100 solar
observations per day during the spin stabilized operation of the SMM.

Shuttle astronauts repaired the solar pointing system in April of 1984.
Normal operations were resumed shortly thereafter.

5.4  Processing Changes.  The effects of the decreased quantity and quality
of ACRIM I data in the spin mode are apparent.  Processing of the data was
affected when the solar pointing system failed -- with changes in effect
during the time of spin mode operation.  Orbit degradation during the last
months of satellite operation has resulted in unreliable solar flux values.
The data are actively being re- calibrated, but official release of data
beyond July of 1989 may not occur.


6.  QUALITY ASSESSMENT

6.1  Data Validation by Producer.  The three ACRIM I sensors agree within
+/-0.04% of their average result.  (Two of ACRIM I's sensors, kept
shuttered most of the time, were used sparingly to calibrate degradation of
the continuously monitoring sensor.)  A measurement precision better than
+/-0.002% was sustained while operating in the self-calibrated mode during
the first 300 days of (normal) SMM operation.  The standard error of single
orbit averages of solar flux during this period was frequently as small as
+/-0.001%.

A sounding rocket solar irradiance experiment in May, 1980, compared two
Active Cavity Radiometers (ACRs) on the rocket with ACRIM I and found
agreement among all five ACR type IV sensors to within +/- 0.05% of their
combined average result.

6.2  Confidence Level/Accuracy Judgment.  Irradiance fluctuations smaller
than 0.01% can be measured with a precision of +/-0.02%. The average
standard error of daily mean results increased from 0.002% during the
normal operation of SMM to 0.02% in the spin mode.  Normal operations
resumed in April 1984 after repairs by the shuttle crew.

In the first 44 days of operation, the total amplitude of solar variation
was .10%.  The largest decrease in irradiance on time scales of several
days can be up to .25%.  In an entire solar cycle (11 years), the
variations can be as much as .40%.

6.3  Usage Guidance.  It is essential to recognize that data accuracy was
affected when the solar pointing system failed in December 1980.  The data
obtained between 1981 and 1983 are considered to be of lower quality. After
shuttle astronauts repaired the precision solar pointing capability of the
SMM satellite in April 1984, the data accuracy improved to earlier levels.
Orbit degradation during the last months of satellite operation may have
affected the data values from July 15, 1989 on.

Solar irradiance values from the SMM ACRIM and Nimbus-7 ERB instruments
have been compared by Foukal (1987).


